cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this software or the results in it, please cite the preprint."
title: "CA1-simplification: Code, run logs and figures for \"Screens Reject, Only Mechanism Confirms\""
authors:
  - family-names: Zhong
    given-names: Peilin
    alias: Larry
    affiliation: "Shady Side Academy, Pittsburgh, PA, USA"
    email: 27zhongp@shadysideacademy.org
version: "4.0"
date-released: 2026-07-20
license: MIT
repository-code: "https://github.com/Larryzpl123/CA1-simplification"
abstract: >-
  Reduced spiking-network models of hippocampal CA1 are validated by asking
  whether they preserve theta and gamma, using spectral peak prominence. In
  these models theta is imposed as a drive. This work shows that combination
  makes the criterion unusable: the drive's harmonic comb both creates false
  gamma (100% false-positive rate against a surrogate null at tight phase
  locking) and MASKS real gamma, and no screen recovers it, because a screen
  can only reject a peak the statistic has already found. Once the comb is
  excised from the spectrum before the maximum is taken, emergent PING gamma
  is recovered and confirmed by a pre-registered mechanistic test: the cycle
  period is affine in the inhibitory decay constant (slope +0.760 +/- 0.113,
  p = 0.0005). Version 4 adds a controlled experiment showing that the switch
  between the null result and the PING result is the input fluctuation and
  not the cell count, and withdraws two claims made in earlier versions.
  Version 1 of this work reached the opposite conclusion and is corrected here.
keywords:
  - computational neuroscience
  - hippocampal CA1
  - PING
  - neural oscillations
  - spectral artifacts
  - surrogate testing
  - pre-registration
  - reproducibility
references:
  - type: article
    title: "Simplification Strategies for Biologically Constrained Hippocampal CA1 Microcircuit Models"
    authors:
